  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(jsonLd)} />
  <div class="v2">
    <V2Enhance />
    <Article33Ribbon />

    <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: 'Home', href: L('/') }, { label: 'Guides', href: L('/guides') }, { label: 'Electricity during outages' }]} />

    <article class="mx-auto max-w-[68ch] px-4 pb-24 pt-12 sm:pb-28">
      <p class="tech-label v2-kicker rule-brass text-lune">Guide · Equipment</p>
      <h1 class="display v2-page-title mt-5 text-white">Keeping the power on during outages</h1>

      <p class="v2-lead mt-6 text-lune-soft">
        The scene is familiar: ONEE cuts power in the middle of the day, the sun is beating down on
        the roof, and yet everything goes dark at your place just like the neighbours'. Many
        homeowners discover at that moment that their panels are useless during an outage. This
        guide explains why, and what needs adding — a hybrid inverter, a battery,
        <strong>EPS</strong> outputs — so the next outage doesn't leave you in the dark.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">Sun overhead, house dark: what's going on?</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        A standard on-grid inverter is designed to inject electricity <em>in phase</em> with the
        grid. As soon as the grid disappears, it shuts down automatically. This legal safety
        requirement is called <strong>anti-islanding</strong>: the inverter must never keep
        producing on a line declared de-energised, at the risk of endangering technicians working
        on it. That's why your panels stop with the grid, even in full sunshine. To keep the power
        on during an outage, you need a hybrid inverter with a dedicated backup output.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">Keeping the power on isn't the same as going off-grid</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        Many people think "riding out an outage" means doing without the grid entirely, like an
        off-grid system powering the whole house indefinitely. That's not what a hybrid inverter's
        backup mode does. It creates a <strong>limited electrical island</strong>: only the circuits
        wired to the <em>EPS outputs</em> (Emergency Power Supply) stay powered, and only as long as
        the battery holds energy. The goal isn't to replace the grid, but to keep the fridge,
        essential lights or the Wi-Fi router alive for the duration of the interruption. This
        nuance changes everything when sizing the installation.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">EPS outputs: the hybrid inverter's backup circuits</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        A hybrid inverter has two types of outputs: normal <em>grid</em> outputs, and
        <strong>EPS</strong> outputs reserved for backup. During installation, an electrician wires
        only the priority circuits onto these EPS outputs — backup lighting, fridge, internet box,
        possibly a pump or water heater depending on battery capacity. The rest of the house follows
        the grid and shuts down normally during the outage. This separation is deliberate: it
        protects the inverter from overloads and lets the battery last longer on genuinely essential
        uses.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">Deye SG series: near-instant switchover, no extra box</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        Deye's SG-series inverters (single-phase SG03LP1, three-phase SG04LP3) integrate backup
        mode natively, with no external box. When the grid goes down, the switchover to the EPS
        outputs is <strong>near-instant (~4–10 ms, UPS-type)</strong>. This delay is so short that
        most sensitive electronics don't notice it, provided they're plugged into the EPS circuits.
        The battery used is low-voltage 48 V LFP, and the inverter offers six configurable TOU
        (Time of Use) windows to charge the battery during off-peak hours and maximise the autonomy
        available at night or during a prolonged outage.
      </p>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-4 text-lune-soft">
        This UPS-mode (uninterruptible power supply) operation is one of the main strengths of this
        range in the Moroccan context, where micro-outages and load shedding can damage electronic
        equipment or interrupt sensitive processes.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">Huawei SUN2000 + Backup Box: a separate box to plan for</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        The Huawei SUN2000 range (L1 single-phase, M1 three-phase) paired with LUNA2000 batteries
        offers excellent integration and advanced monitoring. For the backup function, Huawei
        requires a separate unit: the <strong>Backup Box</strong>. Once installed, it takes over
        the backup circuits with a <strong>very fast</strong> switchover, fast enough for most
        household uses (lights, standby devices, fridge). The real difference from Deye isn't speed
        but the fact that an extra box is needed.
      </p>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-4 text-lune-soft">
        One point to check when choosing: depending on model and firmware, the
        <strong>three-phase SUN2000 M0 may not offer a backup function</strong>. If power
        continuity matters to you, confirm the backup compatibility of the exact reference, or lean
        towards the M1 or another range.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">Hybrid without a battery: "battery-ready"</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        It's entirely possible to install a hybrid inverter without a battery at first. This is
        called a <em>battery-ready</em> configuration. The inverter then works like a standard
        on-grid system: it produces, self-consumes, and, where Law 82-21 allows it, injects a
        surplus onto the grid. The difference is that it's sized to accept batteries later, without
        rewiring everything. However, without a battery, there's no EPS backup possible: the backup
        outputs have no energy to distribute if the grid goes down. Backup only becomes operational
        once a battery is connected.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">What determines backup duration: the battery</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        The EPS switchover only lasts as long as the battery allows. For essential uses (LED
        lighting, fridge, internet box), a battery of 5 to 10 kWh can cover several hours to a full
        night depending on the actual consumption of the connected circuits. If the panels produce
        during the outage (a daytime outage), the hybrid inverter can recharge the battery in real
        time and extend backup almost indefinitely as long as the sun is shining. This is where the
        hybrid system shows its full value compared to a simple generator.
      </p>

